For the detection urea, make sure that all conditions were optimized. As Fig. 4
                        a delineative, upon increasing of urea concentration (0, 0.00167, 0.00833, 0.0167, 0.0833, 0.167, 0.083, 1.67, 3.33, 5, 6.67, 8.33, 16.7, 33.3, 50, 66.7, 83.3, 167 mM), along with the fluorescence intensity decreased gradually. The Fig. 4b displays the relationship between the fluorescence intensity ratio I/I0 (where I and I0 are fluorescence intensity of BCDs-SiO2 composites in the presence or absence urea) and urea concentration. Notably, when the urea concentrations within the range of 0 to 0.0833 mM (Fig. 4b inset) shows a good relationship. The regression equation was found to be Y = -0.34 [C urea] + 0.53 (R2 = 0.992). Meanwhile, when the urea concentration in the range of 0.0833–6.67 mM (Fig. S8), it also exhibits a good relationship, with the regression equation was Y = -0.0335 [C urea] + 0.502 (R2 = 0.988). The detection limit of urea was as low as 1.67 μM. Additionally, comparing with previous fluorescence sensors (Table.1
                        ), it can find that our method shows excellent characteristics, such as lower detection time, high sensitivity and selectivity. Furthermore, another important performance of sensors is their specificity. Based on the special environment of urea, we selected some interferences (Na+, K+, Mg2+, Ala, Phe, His, Gly, Thr, and Leu) to evaluate their effect on the fluorescence of BCDs-SiO2 composites. Firstly, we investigated whether the interferences affected the fluorescence of the BCDs-SiO2 composites. The results prove (Fig. 4c, red bars) that the sensor was not affected by these substances. Secondly, when these substances coexist with urea (Fig. 4c, black bars), it did not affect the ability of urea to quench the fluorescence of BCDs-SiO2 composites. Meanwhile, the specific test samples were observed under UV-light (λex = 360 nm), it was obvious that the BCDs-SiO2 composites was superior to the identification of urea on-site (Fig. 4d). Thus, BCDs-SiO2 composites have excellent specificity to detect urea.
